Going to be real, clicked on "replies" and I did expect what you all expected but I was so pleasantly surprised. Well done you random internet strangers. Well done. 

Also, from the 1% ratio viewer here, I miss you. Ya...felt just as weird to write too. But it's the truth. You, Zach, don't need me to say this because common sense is something your hardass dad (I say that with a smile) instilled it in you but obviously, take all the time you need.

YOU will grow around this pain and YOU will expand. The pain? The pain will stay the same size. I say that for any of you strangers reading this because it's a truth that absolutely helped me and I hope it helps one of you if you need it. 

I thought this specific biblical teaching was apropos:
If ye endure chastening, God dealeth with you as with sons; for what son is he whom the father chasteneth not? (Hebrews 12:7)
Translation: Son, I was hard on you because that‚Äôs what fathers do ‚Äî discipline hurts now, but it builds the man you‚Äôll become.

author: @amangaming5760
text:
@@RicardoSanchez-Virto-f7r The New Testament (NT), written ~AD 50‚Äì100, has over 5,800 Greek manuscripts and 20,000+ in other languages (e.g., Latin), totaling over 25,000 copies, far exceeding other ancient texts. The earliest fragment (P52) dates to ~AD 125, just decades from the originals, and complete manuscripts like Codex Sinaiticus date to ~AD 325‚Äì350. The Old Testament (OT), composed ~1400‚Äì400 BC, has fewer but significant manuscripts, with the Dead Sea Scrolls (~3rd century BC‚Äì1st century AD) providing the oldest copies, some within centuries of the originals, and the Leningrad Codex (~AD 1008) offering a complete Hebrew text.
Compared to other ancient works, the Bible‚Äôs manuscript evidence is unmatched in quantity and proximity to the originals. For example, Homer‚Äôs Iliad (~700 BC) has ~1,900 manuscripts with a ~300-year gap to the earliest fragment, while Plato‚Äôs works (~347 BC) have ~238 manuscripts with a ~1,200-year gap. Other texts like Caesar‚Äôs Gallic Wars (~44 BC, ~251 manuscripts, ~850-year gap) and Tacitus‚Äô Annals (~AD 100, ~36 manuscripts, ~700-year gap) pale in comparison to the NT‚Äôs volume and the OT‚Äôs early attestation via the Dead Sea Scrolls.

author: @howard7997
text:
‚Äã@@RicardoSanchez-Virto-f7r if believing in Jesus, and the price he paid on that old wooden cross for sins He did not commit makes me weak, I will take weak.

If facing the awful things I have done in my life, acknowledging them with no excuses or curtain to hide behind, being broken by what I have done and asking Him for forgiveness. Setting my mind against my sins and temptations so that they do not rule my life makes me weak, I will take weak.

 If forgiving those who have hurt and scarred me in my life, to the point it no longer affects me and I can genuinely pray for their wellbeing makes me weak, I will take weak. If going to those people, showing them love and growing my relationship with them makes me weak, I will take weak.

If sitting before those I have harmed or offended in my life, looking them in the eye and telling them I am truly sorry for the hurt and pain I caused them makes me weak, I will take weak.

If while going through my day, praying for God to use and guide me and being prepared to truly answer that call in any way when called upon makes me weak, I will take weak.

If going to my knees in prayer, praying for healing and blessings for others that are sick or hurting. Putting my needs behind others and standing up for truth makes me weak, I will take weak.

If walking and growing with God, becoming less day by day, year by year of the man I was and more of the man He's shaping me to be. Kinder, more quick to forgive, slower to anger, quicker to listen and slower to speak, more loving and less judgemental of others. If that makes me weak, I will take weak.

Being forgiven when you know you don't deserve it. Accepting blessings when you know you have not earned them. Being freely loved in a way that removes your burdens, breaks your chains and makes you want to be a better person. If that makes me weak, I will take weak.

The truth I have found in my life is that on my own I am weak, but when Jesus walks with me, I am made strong!

author: @duke-c3z
text:
1. Historical Evidence for Jesus‚Äô Resurrection. Jesus‚Äô death by crucifixion is undisputed among historians. The empty tomb, eyewitness claims, and transformation of the disciples (who went from hiding in fear to boldly dying for their belief) are hard to explain without a real resurrection.

2. Existence of Jesus Confirmed by Non-Christian Sources - Roman and Jewish historians (Tacitus, Josephus, Pliny the Younger) confirm Jesus lived, was crucified under Pilate, and had devoted followers. These are independent, non-biblical sources.

3. Cosmological Argument (Origin of the Universe). Everything that begins to exist has a cause. The universe began to exist (confirmed by science: Big Bang). Therefore, the universe has a cause outside of space, time, and matter ‚Üí consistent with God. 

4. Fine-Tuning of the Universe. The laws/constants of physics are so precisely balanced that even slight changes would make life impossible. This makes more sense if the universe was designed than if it‚Äôs just chance.

5. Moral Argument
	‚Ä¢	If objective moral values exist (e.g., ‚Äúmurdering children is always wrong‚Äù), they require a transcendent source. Without God, morality is just opinion, but we all act as if certain things are truly right or wrong.

author: @Stevo.100
text: When he mentioned the maids that really impacted me, because I just started working as a support worker and I have a couple of clients who are very old, my job is to basically help them out with pretty simple things, shopping, cleaning up, helping them with their phone/tv, you know basic things like that. What's so sad is, the people I work for they have family where they live, some have quite a lot of family. But their family doesn't want to help. One of my clients literally none of their daughters or sisters come to visit her, her daughter (who I worked with in a restaurant about 15 years ago, so I know her) only lives up the road from her and never visits her, never helps her, doesn't even call. So what Asmon did, he might not have thought it was a big deal, but it was a big deal. To show your father you loved him that much that you wanted to be the one to help him, that would have been something he noticed and loved.

text: Bravery, not vulnerability. No one will be able to hurt Asmongold for him having put this video out.

author: @rivalx288
text: @@SaltpeterTaffy Well its a bit of both. More than one sentiment can be represented at a time. Speaking to a public audience about a personal loss such as a death is absolutely a vulnerable position as well as a brave one as you said.

author: @imasonite
text: ‚Äã@@SaltpeterTaffy Bravery is not the absence of fear, but the choice to move forward in spite of it. To be brave, you must first admit your own vulnerability: the chance of failure, rejection, pain, or loss. Without that exposure, there is nothing real to overcome, and no true courage in the act. Vulnerability gives bravery its meaning, because it shows you know the risks yet still act. In this way, courage is not about being unbreakable, but about choosing to stand firm while uncertain and exposed.

author: @SaltpeterTaffy
text: ‚Äã@@rivalx288 Vulnerability is the negative aspect of this act of bravery. Vulnerability, by definition, is a state that can be exploited by those who wish to do you harm.

author: @imasonite
text:
@@SaltpeterTaffy Fear and vulnerability are inseparable, fear exists only because we know we can be hurt, rejected, or lose something we value. If we were truly invulnerable, fear would have no meaning. That‚Äôs why vulnerability gives bravery its depth: courage is not just feeling fear, but recognizing the risks it points to and choosing to move forward anyway.

A good start is to read "The Courage to Be" by Paul Tillich.

It‚Äôs a classic in existential philosophy that explores the relationship between fear, anxiety, vulnerability, and what it really means to have courage in the face of life‚Äôs uncertainties. Tillich breaks down how our awareness of fragility and mortality shapes both our fears and our capacity for bravery.

text:
Sam: It‚Äôs all wrong By rights we shouldn‚Äôt even be here. But we are. It‚Äôs like in the great stories Mr. Frodo. The ones that really mattered. Full of darkness and danger they were, and sometimes you didn‚Äôt want to know the end. Because how could the end be happy. How could the world go back to the way it was when so much bad happened. But in the end, it‚Äôs only a passing thing, this shadow. Even darkness must pass. A new day will come. And when the sun shines it will shine out the clearer. Those were the stories that stayed with you. That meant something. Even if you were too small to understand why. But I think, Mr. Frodo, I do understand. I know now. Folk in those stories had lots of chances of turning back only they didn‚Äôt. Because they were holding on to something.

Frodo: What are we holding on to, Sam?

Sam : That there‚Äôs some good in this world, Mr. Frodo. And it‚Äôs worth fighting for.

author: @Alteori
text:
I can't imagine the pain you must be feeling from missing him. I dread the day of losing mine bc he is my world. But know that he lives on in you. You are his legacy and I know he is so proud of you for being his son. 

The best thing for a daddy is knowing his baby lives on and is well. 

You keep his memory, and that of your mom's, alive and you hold close to your heart all the good times. Soon, your tears of sorrow will turn into tears of joy from your papa's memories and the honor you have of knowing him and loving him. I'm glad you got to say goodbye. 

Your dad was a hardass and a badass and he always will be.  May he and your mama rest well, or continue on to their next adventure.üíó

You're so incredibly strong for dealing with all this by yourself. My best wishes for you, take your time.

author: @RueTempest
text:
I lost my grandfather as well.
He had dementia, and everything went downhill so quickly.
He became confused and sometimes violent. We had to restrain him from trying to steal the truck to go look for Grandma ‚Äî she had passed away just two months earlier.
Watching him lose everything that made him him was one of the hardest parts.
He was gone long before his heart rested.
Loss is hard, but the ones we love will forever live within us.
Every lesson they taught us, every laugh we shared, and every memory we made ‚Äî they left a part of themselves in us.
They helped build us up, made us stronger, and shaped us into who we are today.  The best parts of your grandpa live within you and I know he is proud of you.

text:
‚Äã@@kaof1958This isn't "science" though, this is emotional response based on emotional connection.

If there is no emotional connection, there is no emotional response.

The generation currently dying off is the boomer generation, and a good portion of the boomer generation were pretty bad people, they literally developed the general cultural identity of the millennial generation which is a mixture of narcissism and SPD (sadistic personality disorder), which is why the Millennials for the most part are obsessed with themselves and if you ever see them do something for others it's usually something to cause them to suffer.

You're going to see a lot of parents dying with no emotional response from their children, his case was one of the fringe cases where his parents were decent people and so is he.

But you shouldn't expect it as a norm, it's about as logical as expecting a winning lottery ticket.

text:
I just watched your video about your father, and I want to say how deeply moved I was by your honesty and vulnerability. Sharing something so personal takes courage, and your words painted a powerful portrait of love, loss, and responsibility.
Losing a parent is never easy, and the way you spoke about your father's final days and your relationship with him was both heartbreaking and beautiful. It reminded me of how important it is to cherish the time we have with those we love.
Thank you for letting us into that part of your life. I hope you find comfort in knowing that your story resonates with many of us, and that you're not alone in your grief.
Sending strength and peace your way.

author: @CarolinaGirl6919
text: Yeah I am two and a half years in after losing my dad and I still can't hang. Don't get me wrong, it definitely gets way way easier and better. but it can still hit me sometimes. We lived together because I'm a single mom that I have my daughter and then I have my dad and we all kind of needed each other. So He was also the man of the house to my daughter myself come up which is a real position I don't care what Anyone says, it is a place in a household, if you're lucky. I didn't realize that he wasn't just my dad. he was the man of my house and a stabilizing force in my life  I was just thinking earlier today that I wanted my daddy, as we would say in the South.

author: @mistahnogood
text:
lost my dad when i was 12y old, 3 days after my birthday... i was young so... still growing up was a tough time, as i made it a tough time by drugs/alcohol and all that surrounds those things.. now 37, my mother seems to weaken in all kinds of ways, as well getting sick again after 2 heavy antibiotics treatments for a months.. it falls back into pneumonia and being extremely tired everyday, as she's sleeping on the couch mostly, has cold shivers as she doesn't store fat in her body.. she is skin over bones but still has some strength in her muscles to move a few meters, has a pacemaker, COPD/asthma, .. etc. I do whatever i can to help her daily, shopping, gardening, keeping her busy and socialize with me.
I don't have any other family members besides my older brother, but he's more occupied with his concerns on his image and internet resourcing and studies on languages or whatever games he plays.. as he lacks empathy and/or can't handle it apparently due to his pdd nos and some other mental problems. 
So it will get tough.. it will get rough.. and after my mom has no strength to carry on and passes.. she can sure as hell know she raised me well, because i don't give up. (even if the feelings tell me there's nothing to life for, better go young and strong than old and in pain).. I'll fixated my caring to my brother.. because he needs me too even if he doesnt like it. And after he goes into the ground, i will still have to reconsider myself to be cared for.. and there's where my story might end, but it doesn't because i don't give up on my friends i made in process of living as well..
Never give up on yourself.. and never give in to feelings, when the fact is... you will always have to fight for living. No surrender, no giving up on your team nor your enemy.
/Time/ is your enemy, the _space_ you are gifted with is a friend worth fighting for.
ok ramble done... take care.. dont give up y'all.

author: @dragarngaming
text: I know it's natural to give condolences for the loss of loved ones, for good reason, but in this instance, I truly feel more like thanking you for sharing him with us. We're all unique, coming from different backgrounds and life experiences, but the life experience he shared with all of us cannot be compared to any other. Rather than being sad for the loss I feel we should celebrate who he was and the unintentional joy that he brought to many. Funny without even trying to be funny. Insightful and witty. Providing a relatable, "IDGAF," opinion on many topics. You take your time dealing with everything you feel you need to take care of. Everyone will still be here, anticipating a "going live" alert, supporters and haters alike. I'm certain you won't read this, but I do want to thank you, from the bottom of my heart, for sharing your father with the world and inspiring a generation of folks to reasonably not GAF about the petty BS and live every moment. Take care, bud!

author: @Butane9000
text:
Zack,

I lost my uncle a few years back. In his possession he had a 2007 Ford Mustang Shelby GT500 numbered car with less than 3,000 miles on it. Original tires even damn near 20 years later in practically pristine condition. My brother bought it so we didn't lose it and I'm buying it from him. I regret the last things I said to him since I lashed out even though as I grew older I respected what he did for the family in taking care of my mother's father. 

Earlier this year I was going through something stressful and he came into my thoughts with all my regrets. When I got home I sat down and simply spoke the words I regretted I didn't say. I suggest you do the same when the time is right. 

In regards to visiting the Vietnam memorial I suggest you do so anyway to honor his memory. I'm sure he'll be with you in spirit along with your mom. 

Take care buddy.

author: @aTOMbomb2077
text: I left a comment to Zach. About how i lost my dad from cancer who was only 59 from chronic lymphomic lymphoma (white bloods cells dont die when there supposed to so they build up in your lymph nodes). When my family found out I actually quit my job moved back home and got to spend a year and a half with him BEST DECISION I EVER MADE as before there was a shot to do a stemcell transplant but his white bloods cells had to be at a certain level before the stemcell transplant and that took a year and a half before his body could take the 50/50 shot of working. I donated my stem cells which made him live an extra 3 months. But man did the chemo wreck him. He looked young for only being 59 after the chemo he looked like he aged 20 years went from loosing all his hair with very little gray hair to when it grew back was all grey. What got him in the end because they hit him with so much chemo to kill his immune system to replace it with mine using my stem cells left him wide open to a simple cold which turned to pneumonia and they had to intubated (life support) and a week later he passed. So yeah 110% FUCKING HATE CANCER

author: @aTOMbomb2077
text: Also forgot to add cancer robbed me of many years i could of spent fishing with my dad which i was looking foward to doing all the time when he retired from work. Also miss all his life advice he had as i was on 31 when he passed. He always seemed to have the right answers for everything

author: @mosselyn5081
text: I'm really sorry you've lost both your parents while you're still so young. I lost my dad in my late 40s and my mom in my mid-50s, both to lung cancer (and COPD). The decline can be much more rapid than you'd expect. My mom was walking and shopping and so forth when I went to stay with her to care for her, in a wheelchair within a week, and dead within 2 weeks. The hospice people told me that kind of rapid decline is common. In time, I hope you can set aside your regrets about what you didn't get to do with your dad and just remember him as he was when he was healthy and the good times you shared. That is what he would want for you as well, I'm certain. Look back with love, not regret.

text:
Asmongold, and anyone else who needs to hear this, it‚Äôs totally normal to have those ‚Äúmissing step‚Äù moments, where you think of things you would normally do or tell those who have recently passed on.  Moments where you feel like you forgot, just for a split second, that they‚Äôre gone.  Calls you should make, or things you need to do for them or tell them.  It‚Äôs okay that you have those moments.

You‚Äôll have times when it feels like things are almost back to normal, and there will be times when it feels like the grief sweeps over and drowns you, and sometimes out or nowhere or over the silliest small things.  And that‚Äôs normal.  That‚Äôs okay, it‚Äôs part of the grieving process.

author: @lancer4224130
text:
So I found my mother dead when I was 9. My dad committed suicide where I was 18 I had to help put him in the body bag because he was a big guy I'm also a big guy 6'6 he was 6'8. There's something that doesn't prepare you for these kinds of things or the regrets that you have afterwards. Though he gave you something that is only yours. He gave you a lot of his personality his trust his moments his life.

There's a lot of regrets we can have in life about what we didn't do during life and I'm not going to say that you're wrong and feeling that That's not the right thing to say. 

What I will say is that you get the ability to share his memories. You get the ability to call the family members and let him know what type of life he had. As much as his story as his alone You are now the person who gets the carry on his legacy. As harsh as that may seem but you can do it with pride and love. This doesn't get easier if you're going to become more capacity to be able to help others in this situation as time goes on. So in giving to others in this kind of situation when they're going through that you'll be able to help them more. I'm sorry for you losing your father this way but I'm glad you had this opportunity to do so.
